            <h3>Operators</h3>
            <p>Java supports various operators for performing operations on data:</p>
            <h4>Arithmetic:</h4>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Addition (+): Adds two numbers together. Example: 5 + 3 = 8</p></li>
                <li><p>Subtraction (-): Subtracts the second number from the first. Example: 7 - 2 = 5</p></li>
                <li><p>Multiplication (*): Multiplies two numbers. Example: 4 * 6 = 24</p></li>
                <li><p>Division (/): Divides the first number by the second. Example: 10 / 2 = 5</p></li>
                <li><p>Modulus/remainder (%): Returns the remainder of the division. Example: 9 % 4 = 1</p></li>
            </ul>
            
            <h4>Assignment:</h4>
            <ul>
                <li><p>= Assignment: Assigns a value to a variable. Example: int x = 5;</p></li>
                <li><p>+= Add and assign: Adds a value to a variable and assigns the result. Example: x += 3; // x becomes 8 </p></li>
                <li><p>-= Subtract and assign: Subtracts a value from a variable and assigns the result. Example: x -= 2; // x becomes 6 </p></li>
                <li><p>*= Multiply and assign: Multiplies a variable by a value and assigns the result. Example: x *= 4; // x becomes 24</p></li>
                <li><p>/= Divide and assign: Divides a variable by a value and assigns the result. Example: x /= 3; // x becomes 8</p></li>
                <li><p>%= Modulus and assign: Calculates the modulus and assigns the result. Example: x %= 5; // x becomes 3</p></li>
            </ul>
            
            <h4>Logical:</h4>
            <ul>
                <li><p>&& Logical AND: Returns true if both conditions are true. Example: (x > 0) && (y < 10)</p></li>
                <li><p>|| Logical OR: Returns true if at least one condition is true. Example: (a < 5) || (b > 7)</p></li>
                <li><p>! Logical NOT (negation): Reverses the logical value of a condition. Example: !(x > 5)</p></li>
            </ul>
            
            <h4>Relational:</h4>
            <ul>
                <li><p>== Equal to: Checks if two values are equal. Example: (x == y)</p></li>
                <li><p>!= Not equal to: Checks if two values are not equal. Example: (a != b)</p></li>
                <li><p>&lt Less than: Checks if the first value is less than the second. Example: (x < 10)</p></li>
                <li><p>&gt Greater than: Checks if the first value is greater than the second. Example: (y > 5)</p></li>
                <li><p>&lt= Less than or equal to: Checks if the first value is less than or equal to the second. Example: (a <= 7)</p></li>
                <li><p>&gt= Greater than or equal to: Checks if the first value is greater than or equal to the second. Example: (b >= 3)</p></li>
            </ul>
            
            <h4>Bitwise:</h4>
            <ul>
                <li><p>& Bitwise AND: Performs a bitwise AND operation. Example: (x & y)</p></li>
                <li><p>| Bitwise OR: Performs a bitwise OR operation. Example: (a | b)</p></li>
                <li><p>^ Bitwise XOR: Performs a bitwise XOR (exclusive OR) operation. Example: (m ^ n)</p></li>
                <li><p>~ Bitwise NOT: Inverts the bits of a value. Example: (~x)</p></li>
                <li><p>&gt&gt Bitwise right shift: Shifts the bits to the right. Example: (x &gt&gt 2)</p></li>
                <li><p>&lt&lt Bitwise left shift: Shifts the bits to the left. Example: (y &lt&lt 3)</p></li>
                <li><p>&gt&gt&gt Unsigned right shift: Shifts the bits to the right, filling with zeros. Example: (z &gt&gt&gt 1)</p></li>
            </ul>
            
            <h4>Increment/Decrement:</h4>
            <ul>
                <li><p>++ Increment: Adds 1 to a variable. Example: x++;</p></li>
                <li><p>-- Decrement: Subtracts 1 from a variable. Example: y--; </p></li>
            </ul>
            

